1
00:01:24,320 --> 00:01:25,355
Grandpa!

2
00:01:25,440 --> 00:01:29,274
You're not supposed to be up here,
looking at that.

3
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:31,796
I just wanted to know.

4
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:35,275
Well, you're old enough, I suppose.

5
00:01:36,120 --> 00:01:38,793
You should know the story.

6
00:01:40,360 --> 00:01:42,555
OK, here we go.

7
00:01:43,480 --> 00:01:46,438
It was 1832.

8
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:50,557
On a night much like this.

9
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:03,230
Charles Carroll was the last surviving
signer of the Declaration of Independence.

10
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,549
He was also a member
of a secret society known as the Masons.

11
00:02:08,120 --> 00:02:10,953
And he knew he was dying.

12
00:02:11,680 --> 00:02:14,069
He woke up his stable boy
in the middle of the night

13
00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:18,631
and ordered him to take him to
the White House to see Andrew Jackson,

14
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:21,757
because it was urgent
that he speak to the president.

15
00:02:22,720 --> 00:02:24,199
Did he talk to him?

16
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:27,358
No. He never got the chance.

17
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:29,715
The president wasn't there that night.

18
00:02:31,160 --> 00:02:34,152
But Charles Carroll had a secret.

19
00:02:34,240 --> 00:02:38,313
So he took into his confidence
the one person he could,

20
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:41,233
my grandfather's grandfather,

21
00:02:41,960 --> 00:02:43,712
Thomas Gates.

22
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:45,916
What was the secret?

23
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:49,595
A treasure.

24
00:02:51,640 --> 00:02:54,632
A treasure beyond all imagining.

25
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:01,557
A treasure that had been
fought over for centuries

26
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:05,872
by tyrants, pharaohs,
emperors, warlords.

27
00:03:06,160 --> 00:03:09,516
And every time it changed hands
it grew larger.

28
00:03:12,360 --> 00:03:14,828
And then suddenly...

29
00:03:15,160 --> 00:03:17,151
it vanished.

30
00:03:18,920 --> 00:03:21,912
It didn't reappear
for more than a thousand years,

31
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:23,752
when knights from the First Crusade

32
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:27,150
discovered secret vaults
beneath the Temple of Solomon.

33
00:03:27,240 --> 00:03:29,629
You see, the knights who found the vaults

34
00:03:29,720 --> 00:03:33,918
believed that the treasure
was too great for any one man -

35
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:35,911
not even a king.

36
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:42,075
They brought the treasure back to Europe
and took the name "the Knights Templar".

37
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:47,398
Over the next century
they smuggled it out of Europe

38
00:03:47,480 --> 00:03:50,278
and they formed a new brotherhood
called the Freemasons,

39
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:53,033
in honour of
the builders of the great temple.

40
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:55,759
War followed.

41
00:03:55,840 --> 00:03:59,628
By the time of the American Revolution
the treasure had been hidden again.

42
00:03:59,720 --> 00:04:01,790
By then the Masons included

43
00:04:01,880 --> 00:04:05,839
George Washington,
Benjamin Franklin, Paul Revere.

44
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:08,552
They knew they had to make sure

45
00:04:08,640 --> 00:04:11,916
the treasure would never fall
into the hands of the British.

46
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:15,959
So they devised a series of clues
and maps to its location.

47
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,713
Over time the clues were lost or forgotten,

48
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:20,870
until only one remained -

49
00:04:20,960 --> 00:04:26,717
and that was the secret that Charles Carroll
entrusted to young Thomas Gates.

50
00:04:32,560 --> 00:04:33,549
Charlotte.

51
00:04:34,360 --> 00:04:37,670
"The secret lies with Charlotte."

52
00:04:38,360 --> 00:04:40,078
Who's Charlotte?

53
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:43,675
Oh, not even Mr Carroll knew that.

54
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:45,478
Now look here, Ben.

55
00:04:45,560 --> 00:04:49,792
The Freemasons
among our Founding Fathers left us clues.

56
00:04:49,880 --> 00:04:51,313
Like these.

57
00:04:51,400 --> 00:04:54,551
The unfinished pyramid.
The all-seeing eye.

58
00:04:55,040 --> 00:04:59,113
Symbols of the Knights Templar,
guardians of the treasure.

59
00:04:59,840 --> 00:05:04,755
- They're speaking to us through these.
- You mean laughing at us.

60
00:05:04,840 --> 00:05:07,513
You know what that dollar represents?

61
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:10,068
The entire Gates family fortune.

62
00:05:10,160 --> 00:05:14,358
Six generations of fools...
chasing after fool's gold.

63
00:05:14,440 --> 00:05:17,716
It's not about the money, Patrick.
It's never been about the money.

64
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:19,870
Come on, son. Time to go.

65
00:05:20,480 --> 00:05:23,153
You can... say your goodbyes.

66
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:31,878
Grandpa?

67
00:05:34,920 --> 00:05:36,558
Are we knights?

68
00:05:39,480 --> 00:05:41,789
Do you want to be?

69
00:05:41,880 --> 00:05:45,156
All right. Um... kneel.

70
00:05:56,360 --> 00:05:58,157
Benjamin Franklin Gates,

71
00:05:58,240 --> 00:06:03,633
you take upon yourself the duty
of the Templars, the Freemasons

72
00:06:03,720 --> 00:06:06,518
and the family Gates.

73
00:06:07,240 --> 00:06:09,196
Do you so swear?

74
00:06:09,280 --> 00:06:11,191
I so swear.

75
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:35,110
I was thinking about
Henson and Peary,

76
00:06:35,200 --> 00:06:39,591
crossing this kind of terrain with nothing
more than dog sleds and on foot.

77
00:06:39,680 --> 00:06:42,240
- Can you imagine?
- It's extraordinary.

78
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:49,917
We getting closer?

79
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,834
Assuming Ben's theory's correct
and my tracking model's accurate,

80
00:06:53,920 --> 00:06:56,514
we should be getting very close.

81
00:06:56,600 --> 00:07:00,070
But don't go by me -
I broke a shoelace this morning.

82
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:06,715
- It's... it's a bad omen.
- Shall we turn around and go home?

83
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:09,837
Or we could pull over
and just throw him out here.

84
00:07:11,640 --> 00:07:12,789
OK.

85
00:07:12,880 --> 00:07:16,350
Riley, you're not missing that little
windowless cubicle we found you in?

86
00:07:16,440 --> 00:07:18,476
No, no. Absolutely not.

87
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:38,559
Why are we stopping?
I thought we were looking for a ship.

88
00:07:38,640 --> 00:07:42,519
- I don't see any ship.
- She's out there.

89
00:07:52,360 --> 00:07:55,670
Look... this is a waste of time.

90
00:07:55,760 --> 00:07:58,638
How could a ship wind up way out here?

91
00:07:58,720 --> 00:08:01,757
Well, I'm no expert, but...

92
00:08:01,840 --> 00:08:04,798
it could be that the hydrothermic properties
of this region

93
00:08:04,880 --> 00:08:07,348
produce hurricane-force ice storms

94
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:11,353
that cause the ocean to freeze
and then melt and then refreeze,

95
00:08:11,440 --> 00:08:15,877
resulting in a semisolid
migrating land mass

96
00:08:15,960 --> 00:08:19,509
that would land a ship right around here.

97
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:08,232
Hello, beautiful.

98
00:09:16,120 --> 00:09:19,396
Have Viktor
check the fuel in the generators.

99
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:24,516
Two years ago, if you hadn't shown up,
hadn't believed the treasure was real,

100
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:26,830
<i>I don't know
if I ever would have found Charlotte.</i>

101
00:09:26,920 --> 00:09:29,559
You would have found it, I have no doubt.

102
00:09:29,640 --> 00:09:33,838
That's why I didn't think it was
as crazy an investment as everyone said.

103
00:09:34,200 --> 00:09:38,239
I'm just relieved that I'm not as crazy
as everyone says. Or said my dad was.

104
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:41,598
Or my granddad. Or my great-granddad.

105
00:09:43,200 --> 00:09:44,918
OK!

106
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,956
Let's go!

107
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:51,554
- Let's go find some treasure.
- Yeah, bring us back something.

108
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:30,916
Oh, God!

109
00:10:33,720 --> 00:10:35,472
You handled that well.

110
00:10:36,520 --> 00:10:38,829
This is it.

111
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:41,071
It's the cargo hold.

112
00:10:52,920 --> 00:10:55,559
Do you think it's in the barrels?

113
00:11:13,640 --> 00:11:15,153
Gunpowder.

114
00:11:18,280 --> 00:11:19,793
OK...

115
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:27,316
Why would the captain
be guarding this barrel?

116
00:11:51,400 --> 00:11:53,311
I found something!

117
00:11:59,640 --> 00:12:01,551
What is it?

118
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:20,436
Do you guys know what this is?

119
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:23,115
Is it a billion-dollar pipe?

120
00:12:24,840 --> 00:12:28,116
It's a meerschaum pipe.
Ah, that is beautiful.

121
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:31,476
Look at the intricacy of the scrollwork
on the stem.

122
00:12:31,560 --> 00:12:35,553
- Is it a million-dollar pipe?
- No, it's a clue.

123
00:12:35,640 --> 00:12:38,279
Let me see that.

124
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:41,356
No, don't break it!

125
00:12:41,440 --> 00:12:43,954
We are one step closer to the treasure,
gentlemen.

126
00:12:44,040 --> 00:12:46,508
<i>Ben, I thought you said that
the treasure would be on the Charlotte.</i>

127
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:49,034
<i>No, "The secret lies with Charlotte."</i>

128
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:51,111
I said it could be here.

129
00:13:07,280 --> 00:13:09,840
It's Templar symbols.

130
00:13:16,040 --> 00:13:17,996
"The legend writ."

131
00:13:18,080 --> 00:13:20,116
"The stain effected."

132
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:23,112
"The key in Silence undetected."

133
00:13:23,680 --> 00:13:26,558
"Fifty-five in iron pen."

134
00:13:27,600 --> 00:13:29,875
"Mr Matlack can't offend."

135
00:13:33,360 --> 00:13:35,430
It's a riddle.

136
00:13:38,480 --> 00:13:40,118
I need to think.

137
00:13:43,520 --> 00:13:45,431
"The legend writ."

138
00:13:45,520 --> 00:13:47,397
"The stain effected."

139
00:13:48,280 --> 00:13:50,191
What legend?

140
00:13:51,160 --> 00:13:55,278
There's the legend of the Templar treasure,
and the stain effects the legend.

141
00:13:55,360 --> 00:13:57,351
How?

142
00:13:57,440 --> 00:13:59,749
"The key in Silence undetected."

143
00:14:00,720 --> 00:14:02,631
Wait.

144
00:14:03,480 --> 00:14:07,359
The legend and the key...
Now there's something.

145
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:08,839
A map.

146
00:14:08,920 --> 00:14:11,593
Maps have legends, maps have keys.

147
00:14:11,680 --> 00:14:13,750
It's a map, an invisible map.
So now...

148
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:17,355
Wait a minute. What do you mean,
"invisible" - "an invisible map"?

149
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:21,558
"The stain effected"
could refer to a dye or a reagent

150
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:24,074
used to bring about a certain result.

151
00:14:24,160 --> 00:14:26,879
Combined with
"The key in Silence undetected",

152
00:14:26,960 --> 00:14:31,795
the implication is that the effect is to make
what was undetectable detectable.

153
00:14:32,480 --> 00:14:36,519
Unless...
"The key in Silence" could be...

154
00:14:36,600 --> 00:14:38,989
Prison.

155
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:41,438
Albuquerque.

156
00:14:41,520 --> 00:14:43,988
See, I can do it too.
Snorkel.

157
00:14:44,080 --> 00:14:46,719
That's where the map is.
Like he said, "Fifty-five in iron pen."

158
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:48,199
"Iron pen" is a prison.

159
00:14:48,280 --> 00:14:53,479
Or it could be, since the primary writing
medium of the time was iron gall ink,

160
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:56,358
the "pen" is... just a pen.

161
00:14:56,440 --> 00:15:00,672
But then why not say a pen?
Why... why say "iron pen"?

162
00:15:01,480 --> 00:15:03,436
Cos it's a prison.

163
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:07,479
Wait a minute. "Iron pen" - the "iron"
does not describe the ink in the pen,

164
00:15:08,320 --> 00:15:11,039
it describes what was penned.

165
00:15:11,120 --> 00:15:14,237
It was "iron" -
it was firm, it was mineral...

166
00:15:14,320 --> 00:15:15,912
No, no, no, that's stupid.

167
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:21,199
It was... It was firm,
it was adamant, it was resolved.

168
00:15:22,920 --> 00:15:24,831
It was resolved.

169
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:27,477
"Mr Matlack can't offend."

170
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:31,075
Timothy Matlack was the official scribe
of the Continental Congress.

171
00:15:31,160 --> 00:15:35,278
Calligrapher, not writer. And to make sure
he could not offend the map,

172
00:15:35,360 --> 00:15:38,989
it was put on the back of a resolution
that he transcribed,

173
00:15:39,080 --> 00:15:42,834
a resolution that 55 men signed.

174
00:15:45,480 --> 00:15:48,199
The Declaration of Independence.

175
00:15:54,600 --> 00:15:58,832
Come on, there's no invisible map on the
back of the Declaration of Independence.

176
00:15:58,920 --> 00:16:01,275
That's clever, really.
A document of that importance

177
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:03,510
would ensure the map's survival.

178
00:16:03,600 --> 00:16:06,239
And you said there were several Masons
signed it, yeah?

179
00:16:06,320 --> 00:16:09,471
Yeah. Nine, for sure.

180
00:16:10,760 --> 00:16:14,150
We'll have to arrange a way to examine it.

181
00:16:14,240 --> 00:16:17,277
This is one of the most important
documents in history.

182
00:16:17,360 --> 00:16:21,558
They're not just gonna let us waltz in there
and run chemical tests on it.

183
00:16:21,640 --> 00:16:24,074
- Then what do you propose we do?
- I don't know!

184
00:16:27,760 --> 00:16:29,876
We could borrow it.

185
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:32,711
Steal it?

186
00:16:34,080 --> 00:16:36,833
- I don't think so.
- Ben...

187
00:16:36,920 --> 00:16:40,230
the treasure of the Knights Templar
is the treasure of all treasures.

188
00:16:40,320 --> 00:16:42,914
Oh, I didn't know that.
Really?

189
00:16:43,720 --> 00:16:47,918
Look, Ben... I understand your bitterness.
I really do.

190
00:16:48,240 --> 00:16:50,231
You've spent your entire life
searching for this treasure,

191
00:16:50,320 --> 00:16:52,436
only to have
the respected historical community

192
00:16:52,520 --> 00:16:56,195
treat you and your family
with mockery and contempt.

193
00:16:56,280 --> 00:16:58,669
You should be able to rub this treasure
in their arrogant faces,

194
00:16:58,760 --> 00:17:01,320
and I want you to have
the chance to do that.

195
00:17:02,280 --> 00:17:03,793
How?

196
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:06,833
We all have our areas of expertise.

197
00:17:07,880 --> 00:17:11,270
You don't think mine are limited
to writing cheques, do you?

198
00:17:11,360 --> 00:17:13,476
In another life...

199
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:19,792
I arranged a number of operations of...
questionable legality.

200
00:17:22,280 --> 00:17:24,555
I'd take his word for it, if I were you.

201
00:17:26,440 --> 00:17:30,479
So don't worry.
I'll make all the arrangements.

202
00:17:32,120 --> 00:17:33,155
No.

203
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:41,194
I'd really need your help here.

204
00:17:41,280 --> 00:17:46,593
Ian... I'm not gonna let you steal
the Declaration of Independence.

205
00:17:46,680 --> 00:17:48,796
OK.

206
00:17:48,880 --> 00:17:52,077
From this point on
all you're going to be is a hindrance.

207
00:17:54,760 --> 00:17:55,510
Hey!

208
00:17:55,600 --> 00:17:59,388
What are you gonna do?
Are you gonna shoot me, Shaw?

209
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,639
Well, you can't shoot me.
There's more to the riddle.

210
00:18:02,720 --> 00:18:05,837
Information you don't have. I do.

211
00:18:05,920 --> 00:18:08,832
I'm the only one who can figure it out,
and you know that.

212
00:18:08,920 --> 00:18:11,150
He's bluffing.

213
00:18:11,240 --> 00:18:13,800
We played poker together, Ian.
You know I can't bluff.

214
00:18:13,880 --> 00:18:16,110
Tell me what I need to know, Ben,

215
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:18,395
or I'll shoot your friend.

216
00:18:18,480 --> 00:18:19,833
Hey!

217
00:18:19,920 --> 00:18:22,150
Quiet, Riley!
Your job's finished here.

218
00:18:26,640 --> 00:18:30,679
Look where you're standing.
All that gunpowder.

219
00:18:30,760 --> 00:18:34,435
You shoot me,
I drop this, we all go up.

220
00:18:35,800 --> 00:18:37,074
Ben...

221
00:18:38,320 --> 00:18:41,312
What happens when the flare burns down?

222
00:18:42,840 --> 00:18:45,354
Tell me what I need to know, Ben.

223
00:18:47,280 --> 00:18:48,838
You need to know...

224
00:18:48,920 --> 00:18:50,797
if Shaw can catch.

225
00:18:56,440 --> 00:18:58,032
Nice try, though.

226
00:19:08,920 --> 00:19:10,831
Get out, Shaw!

227
00:19:19,120 --> 00:19:20,712
Fool!

228
00:19:24,920 --> 00:19:26,638
Riley, get over here!

229
00:19:31,880 --> 00:19:34,314
- What is this?
- Smuggler's hold. Get in!

230
00:19:39,640 --> 00:19:40,993
Move! Get out of here!

231
00:19:41,080 --> 00:19:42,638
- What?
- Move! Get out!

232
00:19:43,800 --> 00:19:45,711
Follow me.

233
00:19:49,200 --> 00:19:50,952
Let's go, let's go!
She's gonna blow!

234
00:19:57,720 --> 00:19:59,836
Get down.

235
00:20:29,520 --> 00:20:32,910
OK, let's go.
Before someone sees the smoke.

236
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:05,272
There's an Inuit village
about nine miles east of here.

237
00:21:05,360 --> 00:21:09,239
- It's popular with bush pilots.
- All right.

238
00:21:13,960 --> 00:21:17,430
- Then what are we gonna do?
- Start making our way back home.

239
00:21:17,520 --> 00:21:21,672
No, I meant about Ian. He's gonna steal
the Declaration of Independence, Ben.

240
00:21:22,880 --> 00:21:24,438
We stop him.

241
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:43,068
Is it really so hard to believe

242
00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:45,515
that someone's gonna try to steal
the Declaration of Independence?

243
00:21:45,600 --> 00:21:47,955
The FBI gets 10,000 tips a week.

244
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:50,315
They're not gonna worry about
something they're sure is safe.

245
00:21:50,400 --> 00:21:52,834
But anyone that can do anything
is gonna think we're crazy.

246
00:21:52,920 --> 00:21:55,912
Anyone crazy enough to believe us
isn't gonna want to help.

247
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:00,596
We don't need someone crazy. But one
step short of crazy, what do you get?

248
00:22:00,680 --> 00:22:02,272
Obsessed.

249
00:22:02,360 --> 00:22:03,952
Passionate.

250
00:22:11,440 --> 00:22:13,670
Excuse me.

251
00:22:18,120 --> 00:22:20,588
- Dr Chase can see you now, Mr Brown.
- Thank you.

