503
00:43:32,760 --> 00:43:33,829
It's...

504
00:43:37,040 --> 00:43:38,598
I have $32...

505
00:43:42,640 --> 00:43:44,392
57 c.

506
00:43:45,040 --> 00:43:47,429
We take Visa.

507
00:43:56,640 --> 00:43:58,915
This is Mike. Sublevel three.
I have an alert.

508
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:01,594
Where are you, Ben?

509
00:44:25,160 --> 00:44:27,628
- Where are you?
- Stop talking.

510
00:44:29,080 --> 00:44:31,230
Start the van.

511
00:44:37,200 --> 00:44:42,194
Ben, the...
the mean Declaration lady's behind you.

512
00:44:46,800 --> 00:44:48,472
Hey.

513
00:44:48,560 --> 00:44:50,994
Oh, it's you. Hello.

514
00:44:51,080 --> 00:44:53,719
Mr Brown, what's going on?
What's that?

515
00:44:54,560 --> 00:44:56,755
- It's a souvenir.
- Really?

516
00:44:56,840 --> 00:44:58,796
Stop chatting and get in the van.

517
00:45:04,360 --> 00:45:06,237
Code red. Code red.
We have a break-in.

518
00:45:06,320 --> 00:45:10,029
Lock it down. Nobody leaves the building.
Get the FBI on the phone.

519
00:45:14,040 --> 00:45:16,554
- Did you enjoy the party?
- Yeah.

520
00:45:20,400 --> 00:45:23,278
- Oh, my God.
- Oh, my God! You did not...?

521
00:45:23,920 --> 00:45:25,956
- No...
- Security! Over here!

522
00:45:26,040 --> 00:45:27,951
- Give me that!
- It's yours. Take it.

523
00:45:28,600 --> 00:45:30,238
Security!

524
00:45:30,320 --> 00:45:34,074
- Over here! Security!
- Got you.

525
00:45:34,800 --> 00:45:35,755
Go.

526
00:45:35,840 --> 00:45:37,796
Viktor! Move!

527
00:45:37,880 --> 00:45:39,871
- We can't just let her go!
- We can. Go!

528
00:45:41,200 --> 00:45:43,760
- Security, over here!
- Wait. No, hold it.

529
00:45:43,840 --> 00:45:45,398
Hold it!

530
00:45:47,520 --> 00:45:48,475
- Wha...?
- Oh, bad.

531
00:45:48,560 --> 00:45:49,959
- What do you want?
- Give me the document.

532
00:45:50,040 --> 00:45:51,951
Bad, bad, bad!

533
00:45:55,600 --> 00:45:57,318
- Let me go!
- Just bring her!

534
00:45:57,400 --> 00:45:58,753
No! No!

535
00:46:05,560 --> 00:46:07,278
- That's...
- Go! Go!

536
00:46:16,760 --> 00:46:18,751
And just who might you be?

537
00:46:22,200 --> 00:46:25,033
- Once we catch them what do we do?
- I'm working on it.

538
00:46:26,880 --> 00:46:28,233
Right turn, right turn.

539
00:46:29,880 --> 00:46:33,475
Why don't you just pass me that
document? Then we can all go home.

540
00:46:45,240 --> 00:46:46,639
Oh, no.

541
00:47:00,720 --> 00:47:02,153
Skidding, skidding, skidding.

542
00:47:08,560 --> 00:47:10,676
- Oh, no!
- Holy Lord!

543
00:47:14,960 --> 00:47:18,669
- Help!
- No! If she falls, the document falls.

544
00:47:19,880 --> 00:47:21,757
Get me next to her.

545
00:47:41,880 --> 00:47:43,711
- Thank you.
- No!

546
00:47:43,800 --> 00:47:46,314
Got it. Go on.

547
00:47:47,240 --> 00:47:48,912
Abigail!

548
00:47:50,560 --> 00:47:52,437
Come on. Jump.

549
00:48:01,240 --> 00:48:05,597
- We lost them.
- That's all right. This... is what we need.

550
00:48:15,440 --> 00:48:18,000
Well done, Gates. Well done.

551
00:48:20,360 --> 00:48:22,874
- Are you all right?
- No! Those lunatics...

552
00:48:22,960 --> 00:48:25,394
- You're not hurt, are you?
- You are all lunatics!

553
00:48:25,480 --> 00:48:26,959
- Are you hungry?
- What?

554
00:48:27,040 --> 00:48:28,359
Are you all right?

555
00:48:28,440 --> 00:48:32,228
Still a little on edge from being shot at,
but I'll be OK. Thanks for asking.

556
00:48:32,320 --> 00:48:35,869
Yeah, well, I'm not all right. Those men
have the Declaration of Independence!

557
00:48:35,960 --> 00:48:39,032
- She lost it?
- They don't have it.

558
00:48:40,720 --> 00:48:44,156
See? OK?
Now could you please stop shouting?

559
00:48:45,200 --> 00:48:48,590
- Give me that!
- You're still shouting. It's starting to annoy.

560
00:48:49,120 --> 00:48:52,430
You'd do well, Dr Chase,
to be a bit more civilised in this instance.

561
00:48:52,720 --> 00:48:55,314
If this is the real one, what did they get?

562
00:48:55,680 --> 00:48:57,398
A souvenir.

563
00:48:57,480 --> 00:49:00,950
I thought it'd be a good idea to have
a duplicate. It turned out I was right.

564
00:49:01,360 --> 00:49:07,469
I actually had to pay for the souvenir and
the real one, so you owe me $35, plus tax.

565
00:49:07,920 --> 00:49:10,718
- Genius.
- Who were those men?

566
00:49:10,800 --> 00:49:13,109
Just the guys we warned you
were gonna steal the Declaration.

567
00:49:13,200 --> 00:49:14,997
And you didn't believe us.

568
00:49:15,080 --> 00:49:17,548
We did the only thing we could do
to keep it safe.

569
00:49:18,720 --> 00:49:20,153
<i>Verdammt! Give me that!</i>

570
00:49:20,240 --> 00:49:22,435
You know something?
You're shouting again.

571
00:49:22,520 --> 00:49:24,397
I'm pretty sure she was swearing, too.

572
00:49:24,480 --> 00:49:27,438
Well, we probably deserve that.

573
00:49:33,720 --> 00:49:35,790
Ladies and gentlemen...

574
00:49:35,880 --> 00:49:40,032
Ladies and gentlemen, my name is
Peter Sadusky. I'm the agent in charge.

575
00:49:40,120 --> 00:49:43,078
I wanna reassure you,
you are not in danger in any way.

576
00:49:43,160 --> 00:49:47,756
If we all cooperate, we'll get through this
with as little frustration as possible.

577
00:49:48,200 --> 00:49:50,111
Thank you.

578
00:49:51,320 --> 00:49:55,836
Get positive IDs. Search everyone,
including the security staff.

579
00:49:55,920 --> 00:49:58,593
If they refuse,
detain them and get warrants.

580
00:49:58,680 --> 00:50:01,069
Yes, Agent Hendricks?
You have something?

581
00:50:01,800 --> 00:50:02,437
Um...

582
00:50:02,520 --> 00:50:06,798
- This isn't a day for "Um..."
- We got a tip several days ago

583
00:50:06,880 --> 00:50:09,792
that someone was going to steal
the Declaration of Independence.

584
00:50:09,880 --> 00:50:12,678
Do we have a name on the tipster?

585
00:50:12,760 --> 00:50:16,196
There was no file opened.
We didn't find the information credible.

586
00:50:17,760 --> 00:50:19,398
How about now?

587
00:50:19,480 --> 00:50:23,359
There is not a treasure map on the back
of the Declaration of Independence.

588
00:50:23,440 --> 00:50:27,194
And there's no chance
anyone can steal this either.

589
00:50:28,160 --> 00:50:31,391
I levelled with you 100 per cent.
Everything I told you was the truth.

590
00:50:31,480 --> 00:50:33,596
I want that document, Mr Brown.

591
00:50:33,960 --> 00:50:36,554
OK, my name's not Brown.
It's Gates.

592
00:50:36,640 --> 00:50:38,915
I levelled with you 98 per cent.

593
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:41,560
Wait a minute, did you just say "Gates"?

594
00:50:42,560 --> 00:50:44,118
Gates?

595
00:50:44,200 --> 00:50:47,590
You're that family with the conspiracy
theory about the Founding Fathers?

596
00:50:47,680 --> 00:50:50,877
- It's not a conspiracy theory.
- Per se.

597
00:50:50,960 --> 00:50:54,635
You know what? I take it back.
You're not liars. You're insane.

598
00:50:54,720 --> 00:50:56,836
There's a copy of the Declaration
on display now?

599
00:50:56,920 --> 00:50:58,990
- Yes, we decided to...
- Leave it there.

600
00:50:59,080 --> 00:51:01,594
The guests know something happened,
but they don't know what.

601
00:51:01,680 --> 00:51:04,717
They got him with a Taser at the service
entrance. He doesn't remember a thing.

602
00:51:04,800 --> 00:51:06,836
Also, we found bullet casings.

603
00:51:06,920 --> 00:51:08,478
Did we get a description
from the other guards?

604
00:51:08,560 --> 00:51:11,438
- Which guards?
- The guards that were fired upon.

605
00:51:11,520 --> 00:51:15,479
There weren't any other guards
on patrol down here.

606
00:51:15,800 --> 00:51:17,870
So...

607
00:51:17,960 --> 00:51:21,032
who was shooting,
who were they shooting at,

608
00:51:21,120 --> 00:51:23,350
and why weren't they getting along?

609
00:51:23,440 --> 00:51:26,159
You can't seriously intend
to run chemical tests

610
00:51:26,240 --> 00:51:29,277
on the Declaration of Independence
in the back of a moving van.

611
00:51:29,360 --> 00:51:30,952
We have a clean-room environment
all set up.

612
00:51:31,040 --> 00:51:34,112
EDS suits, a particulate air filtration
system, the whole shebang.

613
00:51:34,200 --> 00:51:36,634
- Really?
- We can't go back there.

614
00:51:36,720 --> 00:51:38,392
What? Why not?

615
00:51:38,480 --> 00:51:42,155
This is the guy. Dr Herbert said
Dr Chase introduced him as Mr Brown.

616
00:51:42,240 --> 00:51:43,468
Not on the guestlist.

617
00:51:43,560 --> 00:51:47,519
Now, the gift-store clerk - she said
he seemed... Well, she said "flustered".

618
00:51:47,600 --> 00:51:50,433
He tried to walk out with a copy
of the Declaration of Independence

619
00:51:50,520 --> 00:51:52,397
without paying.

620
00:51:52,480 --> 00:51:54,357
He paid with a Visa.

621
00:51:54,440 --> 00:51:57,477
"Charge to Benjamin Gates."

622
00:51:57,560 --> 00:52:00,154
A credit-card slip?

623
00:52:00,240 --> 00:52:01,832
Dude, we're on the grid.

624
00:52:01,920 --> 00:52:04,639
They'll have your records from forever.
They'll have my records from forever.

625
00:52:04,720 --> 00:52:08,110
I know. I know. It's only a matter of minutes
before the FBI shows up at my front door.

626
00:52:08,200 --> 00:52:10,156
What do we do?

627
00:52:10,240 --> 00:52:13,038
- We need those letters.
- What letters?

628
00:52:15,240 --> 00:52:17,117
You know, get off the road,
take a right.

629
00:52:17,200 --> 00:52:18,952
What letters?

630
00:52:19,800 --> 00:52:24,635
You have the original Silence Dogood
letters? Did you steal those, too?

631
00:52:24,720 --> 00:52:26,711
We have scans of the originals.

632
00:52:26,800 --> 00:52:29,519
- Quiet, please.
- How'd you get scans?

633
00:52:29,600 --> 00:52:32,990
Oh, I know the person
who has the originals. Now shush.

634
00:52:35,920 --> 00:52:40,118
- Why do you need them?
- She really can't shut her mouth, can she?

635
00:52:40,200 --> 00:52:43,749
I'll tell you what, look.
I will let you hold onto this

636
00:52:43,840 --> 00:52:46,513
if you'll promise to shut up, please.

637
00:52:46,600 --> 00:52:49,034
Thank you.

638
00:52:49,720 --> 00:52:52,029
- Ben, you know what you have to do.
- I know what to do.

639
00:52:52,120 --> 00:52:54,714
I'm just trying to think
of anything else we could do.

640
00:52:54,800 --> 00:52:57,394
Well, not to be a... nudge,

641
00:52:57,480 --> 00:53:01,314
but you do realise how many people
we have after us.

642
00:53:01,400 --> 00:53:04,551
We probably have
our own satellite by now.

643
00:53:05,680 --> 00:53:10,913
It took you all of two seconds to decide
to steal the Declaration of Independence.

644
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:14,754
Yeah, but I didn't think I was gonna
personally have to tell my dad about it.

645
00:53:14,840 --> 00:53:17,400
Hey, not cool! Not cool!

646
00:53:17,480 --> 00:53:19,471
Let me go!

647
00:53:19,560 --> 00:53:21,755
OK. You're let go. Go, shoo.

648
00:53:21,840 --> 00:53:24,035
I'm not going. Not without the Declaration.

649
00:53:24,120 --> 00:53:26,918
You're not going with the Declaration.

650
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:30,515
Yes, I am. I'm not letting it
out of my sight, so I'm going.

651
00:53:30,600 --> 00:53:33,672
Wait. You're not going with us
with the Declaration.

652
00:53:33,760 --> 00:53:36,911
- Yes, I am.
- No, you're not.

653
00:53:37,920 --> 00:53:40,036
Look, if you wanted to leave me behind,

654
00:53:40,120 --> 00:53:43,430
you shouldn't have told me
where you were going.

655
00:53:58,480 --> 00:54:00,391
Clear.

656
00:54:01,080 --> 00:54:03,275
What the...

657
00:54:04,640 --> 00:54:07,279
Now we're getting somewhere.

658
00:54:08,200 --> 00:54:11,875
<i>They're digital scans of letters
to the editor of The New England Courant.</i>

659
00:54:11,960 --> 00:54:14,554
Written 1722.

660
00:54:14,640 --> 00:54:18,792
They're all from the same person.
"Your humble servant, Silence Dogood."

661
00:54:33,760 --> 00:54:35,637
Gentlemen...

662
00:54:35,720 --> 00:54:39,759
why is this word capitalised?

663
00:54:40,760 --> 00:54:43,479
Because it's important?

664
00:54:45,600 --> 00:54:47,830
Because it's a name.

665
00:54:47,920 --> 00:54:50,798
OK, I got it.
When Ben Franklin was only 15 years old

666
00:54:50,880 --> 00:54:53,678
he secretly wrote 14 letters
to his brother's newspaper

667
00:54:53,760 --> 00:54:57,275
pretending to be a middle-aged widow
named Silence Dogood.

668
00:54:57,360 --> 00:54:59,954
These letters were written
by Benjamin Franklin.

669
00:55:06,640 --> 00:55:08,915
Looks OK.

670
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:11,514
- Park a couple of blocks away.
- Well, how long do you think we got?

671
00:55:11,600 --> 00:55:15,036
I'm gonna give them a couple of hours
at least. I hope.

672
00:55:15,120 --> 00:55:18,954
What do we do about her?
I've got some duct tape in the back.

673
00:55:19,040 --> 00:55:21,190
No, that won't be necessary.
She won't be any trouble.

674
00:55:21,280 --> 00:55:24,352
- Promise you won't be any trouble.
- I promise.

675
00:55:24,440 --> 00:55:26,317
See? She's curious.

676
00:55:29,960 --> 00:55:34,272
Here's what I got on Gates. A degree
in American History from Georgetown,

677
00:55:34,360 --> 00:55:36,430
a degree in Mechanical Engineering
at MIT,

678
00:55:36,520 --> 00:55:40,877
Navy ROTC and Naval Diving
and Salvage Training Centre.

679
00:55:41,560 --> 00:55:44,154
What in the world did this guy
want to be when he grew up?

680
00:55:44,240 --> 00:55:46,151
We keep our focus on Gates.

681
00:55:46,240 --> 00:55:48,435
Run him to ground.

682
00:55:48,520 --> 00:55:52,149
Compile a family-and-friends list.
Closest relative first.

683
00:55:52,600 --> 00:55:55,239
I want to find out who this guy is.

684
00:56:03,600 --> 00:56:04,828
Dad.

685
00:56:07,120 --> 00:56:09,031
Where's the party?

686
00:56:09,560 --> 00:56:13,189
Well... I'm in a little trouble.

687
00:56:14,200 --> 00:56:16,714
- Is she pregnant?
- Well, if she is,

688
00:56:16,800 --> 00:56:21,078
are you gonna leave the woman carrying
your grandchild standing out in the cold?

689
00:56:21,160 --> 00:56:23,435
I look pregnant?

690
00:56:27,960 --> 00:56:31,077
This better not be about
that dumb treasure.

691
00:56:36,120 --> 00:56:38,634
Well, have a seat.
Make yourselves comfortable.

692
00:56:38,720 --> 00:56:42,429
There's some pizza.
It's still warm, I think.

693
00:56:42,520 --> 00:56:43,999
Dad...

694
00:56:45,920 --> 00:56:50,630
I need the Silence Dogood letters.
Yeah, it's about the treasure.

695
00:56:50,720 --> 00:56:52,676
And he dragged you two
into this nonsense?

696
00:56:52,760 --> 00:56:55,115
- Literally.
- I volunteered.

697
00:56:55,200 --> 00:56:58,272
Well, unvolunteer,
before you waste your life.

698
00:56:58,360 --> 00:57:01,272
- Knock it off, Dad.
- Sure, sure, I know, I'm the family kook.

699
00:57:01,360 --> 00:57:03,510
I have a job, a house, health insurance.

700
00:57:03,600 --> 00:57:07,593
At least I had your mother, for however
brief a time. At least I had you.

701
00:57:07,680 --> 00:57:09,875
What do you have? Him?

702
00:57:12,000 --> 00:57:15,037
Look, if you just give us the letters,
we're gone.

703
00:57:15,120 --> 00:57:16,951
You disappoint me, Ben.

704
00:57:17,040 --> 00:57:21,909
Well, maybe that's the real Gates-family
legacy. Sons who disappoint their fathers.

705
00:57:23,360 --> 00:57:25,874
Get out. Take your troubles with you.

706
00:57:31,080 --> 00:57:33,469
<i>I found the Charlotte.</i>

707
00:57:37,720 --> 00:57:39,631
<i>The Charlotte?</i>

708
00:57:40,440 --> 00:57:43,193
- You mean she was a ship?
- Yeah, she was beautiful.

709
00:57:43,280 --> 00:57:44,235
It was amazing, Dad.

710
00:57:44,320 --> 00:57:46,959
And the treasure?

711
00:57:47,040 --> 00:57:49,679
No, no. But we found another clue
that led us here.

712
00:57:49,760 --> 00:57:52,320
Yeah, and that'll lead you
to another clue.

713
00:57:52,400 --> 00:57:54,868
And that's all you'll ever find,
is another clue. Don't you get it, Ben?

714
00:57:54,960 --> 00:57:56,359
I finally figured it out.

715
00:57:56,440 --> 00:57:59,512
The legend says that the treasure
was buried to keep it from the British.

716
00:57:59,600 --> 00:58:02,239
But what really happened
was the legend was invented,

717
00:58:02,320 --> 00:58:06,393
to keep the British occupied
searching for buried treasure.

718
00:58:06,480 --> 00:58:09,597
The treasure is a myth.

719
00:58:09,680 --> 00:58:11,910
I refuse to believe that.

720
00:58:16,920 --> 00:58:20,993
Well, you can believe what you want.
You're a grown person. What am I doing?

721
00:58:21,080 --> 00:58:24,197
Do what you want, Ben.
Do what you want.

722
00:58:25,640 --> 00:58:30,191
He's probably right. You don't even know
if there is another clue.

723
00:58:32,160 --> 00:58:36,472
Well, I can think of a way where we could
find out. And we can find out right now.

724
00:58:53,880 --> 00:58:55,871
Looks like animal skin.

725
00:58:56,520 --> 00:58:59,512
- How old is it?
- At least 200 years.

726
00:58:59,600 --> 00:59:03,149
- Really? You sure?
- Pretty darn.

727
00:59:03,240 --> 00:59:05,629
Now if this thing's in invisible ink,
how do we look at it?

728
00:59:05,720 --> 00:59:06,948
Throw it in the oven.

729
00:59:07,040 --> 00:59:08,553
- No.
- Uh-uh.

730
00:59:08,640 --> 00:59:11,200
Ferrous sulphate inks
can only be brought out with heat.

731
00:59:11,280 --> 00:59:14,317
- Yes, but this...
- It's very old.

732
00:59:14,400 --> 00:59:19,872
This is very old, and we can't
risk compromising the map.

733
00:59:19,960 --> 00:59:21,075
You need a reagent.

734
00:59:21,160 --> 00:59:23,754
Dad, it's really late.
Why don't you get some rest?

735
00:59:23,840 --> 00:59:26,229
I'm fine.

736
00:59:26,320 --> 00:59:28,072
Lemons.

737
00:59:34,400 --> 00:59:36,630
- You can't do that.
- But it has to be done.

738
00:59:36,720 --> 00:59:40,793
Then someone who is trained to handle
antique documents is gonna do it.

739
00:59:41,760 --> 00:59:43,591
OK.

740
00:59:45,360 --> 00:59:46,998
OK.

741
00:59:48,120 --> 00:59:50,998
Now, if there is a secret message,

742
00:59:51,080 --> 00:59:56,200
it'll probably be marked by a symbol
in the upper right-hand corner.

743
00:59:56,280 --> 00:59:57,793
That's right.

744
01:00:01,440 --> 01:00:03,749
I am so getting fired for this.

745
01:00:33,920 --> 01:00:36,593
I told you. You need heat.

746
01:00:53,880 --> 01:00:55,518
See?

747
01:00:58,080 --> 01:01:00,116
- We need more juice.
- We need more heat.

748
01:01:14,040 --> 01:01:16,315
That's not a map.

749
01:01:16,400 --> 01:01:19,392
- Is it?
- More clues. What a surprise.

750
01:01:19,480 --> 01:01:21,072
Are those latitudes and longitudes?

751
01:01:21,160 --> 01:01:23,594
That's why we need
the Silence Dogood letters.

752
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:26,638
- That's the key?
- Yeah. "The key in Silence undetected."

753
01:01:26,720 --> 01:01:28,278
Dad, can we have the letters now?

754
01:01:28,360 --> 01:01:32,638
Will somebody please explain to me
what these magic numbers are?

755
01:01:32,720 --> 01:01:35,029
- It's an Ottendorf cipher.
- That's right.

756
01:01:35,120 --> 01:01:36,872
Oh, OK.

757
01:01:36,960 --> 01:01:39,758
- What's an Ottendorf cipher?
- They're just codes.

758
01:01:39,840 --> 01:01:43,992
Each of these three numbers
corresponds to a word in a key.

759
01:01:44,080 --> 01:01:46,753
Usually a random book
or a newspaper article.

760
01:01:46,840 --> 01:01:48,876
In this case,
the Silence Dogood letters.

761
01:01:48,960 --> 01:01:51,269
So it's like the page number
of the key text,

762
01:01:51,360 --> 01:01:54,511
the line on the page,
and the letter in that line.

763
01:01:54,600 --> 01:01:57,114
So, Dad, where are the letters?

764
01:01:57,200 --> 01:02:01,990
You know, it's just by sheer happenstance
that his grandfather...

765
01:02:02,080 --> 01:02:03,195
- Dad.
...even found them.

766
01:02:03,280 --> 01:02:05,475
They were in an antique desk
from the press room...

767
01:02:05,560 --> 01:02:07,152
<i>- Dad.
...of The New England Courant.</i>

768
01:02:07,240 --> 01:02:10,152
- That's a newspaper.
- Dad, where are the letters?

769
01:02:10,240 --> 01:02:12,879
I don't have them, son.

770
01:02:12,960 --> 01:02:15,599
- What?
- I don't have them.

771
01:02:22,200 --> 01:02:23,519
Where are they?

772
01:02:23,600 --> 01:02:26,956
I donated them to the Franklin Institute
in Philadelphia.

773
01:02:27,520 --> 01:02:29,431
Time to go.

774
01:02:30,440 --> 01:02:34,877
I still can't believe it. All this time
no one knew what was on the back.

775
01:02:34,960 --> 01:02:36,359
The back of what?

776
01:02:36,440 --> 01:02:38,476
No!

777
01:02:38,560 --> 01:02:40,949
- Oh, my God. Oh, my God.
- I know.

778
01:02:41,040 --> 01:02:43,508
Oh, my God. What have you done?
This is... this is the...

779
01:02:43,600 --> 01:02:46,239
- I know!
- This is the Declaration of Independence.

780
01:02:46,320 --> 01:02:49,357
Yes. And it's very delicate.

781
01:02:49,440 --> 01:02:51,556
You stole it?

782
01:02:51,640 --> 01:02:56,760
Dad, I can explain, but I don't have time.
It was necessary. And you saw the cipher.

783
01:02:56,840 --> 01:02:59,434
And that will lead to another clue,
and that will lead to another clue!

784
01:02:59,520 --> 01:03:02,751
There is no treasure.
I wasted 20 years of my life.

785
01:03:02,840 --> 01:03:05,559
And now you've destroyed yours.

786
01:03:06,360 --> 01:03:08,476
And you pulled me into all this.

787
01:03:09,240 --> 01:03:11,913
Well, we can't have that.

788
01:03:16,360 --> 01:03:18,828
Come in!

789
01:03:18,920 --> 01:03:20,831
I'm in here.

790
01:03:21,760 --> 01:03:23,671
FBI, right?

791
01:03:27,400 --> 01:03:29,675
You gonna untie me?

792
01:03:32,240 --> 01:03:34,629
And you have no idea where he's going?

793
01:03:34,720 --> 01:03:38,599
- Well, wouldn't I have told you if I did?
- Would you?

794
01:03:38,680 --> 01:03:40,716
He tied me to a chair.

795
01:03:40,800 --> 01:03:44,679
The garage is empty, but there's a Cadillac
De Ville registered to Patrick Gates.

796
01:03:44,760 --> 01:03:46,751
And he stole my car.

797
01:03:47,160 --> 01:03:50,675
Don't worry, Mr Gates, we'll find your car.
And your son.

798
01:03:53,200 --> 01:03:55,430
Your dad's got a sweet ride.

799
01:03:55,520 --> 01:03:58,239
I think we should change clothes.

800
01:03:58,320 --> 01:04:00,754
We look kind of conspicuous,
don't you think?

801
01:04:00,840 --> 01:04:03,718
I'd love to go shopping, too,
but we have no money.

802
01:04:03,800 --> 01:04:05,711
Here, I took this from his house.

803
01:04:05,800 --> 01:04:09,349
He usually tucks a few hundred dollars
somewhere between those pages.

804
01:04:09,440 --> 01:04:13,433
<i>- Common Sense. How appropriate.
- When are we gonna get there?</i>

805
01:04:13,520 --> 01:04:16,956
I'm hungry. This car smells weird.

806
01:04:59,600 --> 01:05:01,670
Excuse me.

807
01:05:01,760 --> 01:05:04,558
Excuse me. Oops, sorry, sir. Excuse me.

808
01:05:04,640 --> 01:05:06,551
That's OK.

809
01:05:12,760 --> 01:05:14,796
S-S-A-N-D.

810
01:05:14,880 --> 01:05:16,472
OK.

811
01:05:17,840 --> 01:05:20,479
You're sure this is right?

812
01:05:21,800 --> 01:05:23,119
OK.

813
01:05:23,200 --> 01:05:24,952
S-S-A...

814
01:05:25,960 --> 01:05:27,678
No, N.

815
01:05:27,760 --> 01:05:30,877
- That is an N.
- It doesn't look like an N.

816
01:05:32,720 --> 01:05:35,871
You know what? Here. Last one. OK?

817
01:05:37,080 --> 01:05:39,275
- One more dollar.
- Thank you.

818
01:05:39,760 --> 01:05:41,830
Go get the last four letters.

819
01:05:41,920 --> 01:05:44,229
Go get 'em, chief. Come on.

820
01:06:01,600 --> 01:06:05,832
OK. "The vision to see the treasured past

821
01:06:05,920 --> 01:06:12,075
comes as the timely shadow crosses
in front of the house of pass and..."

822
01:06:12,160 --> 01:06:14,720
"Pass and..." what?

823
01:06:27,640 --> 01:06:30,200
"Pass and..."

824
01:06:55,200 --> 01:06:57,589
What's going on?

825
01:06:59,640 --> 01:07:01,471
- I'm not sure.
- What's up?

826
01:07:03,880 --> 01:07:07,190
So you show up at your father's door
and say you're in trouble

827
01:07:07,280 --> 01:07:10,955
and the first thing he assumes
is I'm pregnant.

828
01:07:11,040 --> 01:07:13,315
Is there a question in there?

829
01:07:13,400 --> 01:07:15,834
I think there's an interesting story
in there.

830
01:07:15,920 --> 01:07:19,799
Well, my father thinks I've been
a little too cavalier in my personal life.

831
01:07:19,880 --> 01:07:22,474
- I see.
- Let me ask you something.

832
01:07:22,560 --> 01:07:25,358
Have you ever told someone -
not a relative - "I love you"?

833
01:07:25,440 --> 01:07:27,556
Yes.

834
01:07:27,640 --> 01:07:30,200
More than one someone?

835
01:07:31,040 --> 01:07:32,439
Yes.

836
01:07:32,520 --> 01:07:34,317
Oh. Well, then my father would say

837
01:07:34,400 --> 01:07:37,631
you've been a little too cavalier
in your personal life, too.

838
01:07:37,720 --> 01:07:41,030
So you get your sense of absolute certainty
from him, do you?

